'''Kiko Matthews''' (born in 1982<ref>Chadband, Ian (1 June 2018). [http://www.espn.co.uk/olympics/story/_/id/23571524/meet-kiko-matthews-brit-rowed-atlantic-alone-unexperienced-earned-world-record-it "Rogue waves, a near capsize and 49 days alone on the Atlantic, what could stop Kiko Matthews?"]. [[ESPN]]</ref>) is a British long-distance rower. On 22 March 2018, she became the fastest female to row the [[Atlantic]], solo and unsupported.<ref>{{cite web |title=British woman breaks Atlantic rowing record months after neurosurgery |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/mar/23/kiko-matthews-fastest-woman-to-row-solo-across-atlantic-record |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref> Matthews rowed the 4819 km from [[Gran Canaria]] to [[Port St. Charles|Port St. Charles, Barbados]] in 49 days 7 hours and 15 minutes.<ref>Thorne, Dan and Swatman, Rachel (16 May 2018). [http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2018/5/how-kiko-matthews-survived-two-tumours-rowed-the-atlantic-and-set-new-records-523138 "How Kiko Matthews survived two tumours and rowed the Atlantic solo to set new records"]. [[Guinnessworldrecords.com]]. Retrieved 1 August 2018.</ref> Through sponsorship of her [[world record]] attempt, Matthews had already raised over £82,000 for [[King's College Hospital]] by 26 March 2018.<ref name="hospital">[[King's College Hospital]] (26 March 2018). [https://supportkings.org.uk/news/kings-patient-kiko-matthews-smashes-world-record-to-become-the-fastest-female-to-solo-row-the-atlantic-ocean/ "King's patient Kiko Matthews smashes world record to become the fastest female to solo row the Atlantic Ocean"]. Retrieved 1 August 2018.</ref><ref name="BBC">[[BBC News]] (23 March 2018). [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-43514525 Kiko Matthews breaks Atlantic rowing record"]. Retrieved 1 August 2018.</ref>
Matthews grew up in [[Herefordshire]]. In 2009, she had a nearly fatal brain tumor, which resulted in [[Cushing's disease]]. She was treated at [[King's College Hospital]], and had to undergo neurosurgery. In August 2017, she had another tumor, which occurred while she was training for the Atlantic crossing.<ref name="hospital"/><ref name="BBC"/>
